<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 94 / Boeing may tie component deals to aircraft sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON and PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Boeing, the world's leading aircraft maker, has started a review of
purchasing policies aimed at directing future contracts for aircraft parts
to countries which buy its aircraft.
The review could result in the Seattle-based company shifting purchases away
from countries, such as Canada, whose governments and airlines have
increasingly opted for European Airbus aircraft.
Although no decisions have been taken, a Boeing official said yesterday the
review was designed to place work in a way which would 'assist in market
access'. Boeing's commercial aircraft division buys components from 323
suppliers in 38 countries outside the US.
The company, which has traditionally controlled about 60 per cent of the
world's commercial aircraft market but has been facing intense competition
from Airbus, is seeking to expand its presence in the fast-growing
Asia-Pacific market by offering sub-contracting work to Japanese and Chinese
manufacturers, and to aircraft makers in other Far Eastern countries.
Japanese manufacturers are responsible for about 20 per cent of the work on
the Boeing 777, the new twin-engine wide-bodied aircraft that will enter
service next year.
Airbus is also stepping up competition in these markets, recently announcing
a Dollars 25m agreement with the China Aviation Supplies Corporation to set
up a flight crew training centre in Beijing. The European consortium has
also been in talks with Japanese manufacturers to interest them in possible
collaboration over a new 800-seat aircraft.
Boeing's move was disclosed by Mr Ron Woodard, president of the company's
commercial aircraft group, in a speech to the Aerospace Industries
Association of Canada.
Mr Woodard complained that the Canadian defence department had not given
Boeing an opportunity to bid on replacements for a fleet of ageing Boeing
707 airliners. Instead, the Canadians bought five twin-engine wide-body
Airbus A-310s.
He noted that Boeing has spent about CDollars 800m (Pounds 370m) annually in
Canada over the past three years. But sales had dwindled to about CDollars
30m a year, all on components and not new aircraft.
'Our Canadian business placement must understandably be market based, as it
is elsewhere,' Mr Woodard said.
'Boeing supports the principal of the level playing field. We don't ask for
special considerations and we don't want to have to compete against special
considerations granted (to) others.'
Mr Woodard's comments have been interpreted as a shot across the bows of
Calgary-based Canadian Airlines International, which is expected to place
sizeable orders over the next few years to replace its Boeing 737
twin-engine, narrow-body fleet.
The Canadian government is also eyeing an order for search-and-rescue
helicopters. Boeing will review its Canadian contracts next week.
An official said that the review will would affect not only 130 contractors
in Canada, but also two plants in Manitoba and Ontario, which are Boeing's
only company-owned manufacturing sites outside the US.
Boeing warns of battle for clients, Page 7
MoD warned not to buy US aircraft, Page 10
</TEXT>
