<HEADLINE>
FT  08 NOV 94 / Surge in output strengthens UK economic upturn: Inflation
fears depress equities and bonds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is expected to revise upwards its estimate of third-quarter
economic growth after official figures yesterday showed that industrial
production grew unexpectedly in the three months to September.
The output figures, which highlight the strong economic platform from which
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, will launch his second Budget in three
weeks' time, were well above City expectations.
With other official data showing third-quarter growth in consumer credit
demand to record levels, fears that the economy might be slowing in a
delayed reaction to tax increases were allayed.
The good economic news contributed to a generally weaker tone on financial
markets. Brokerage houses argued that the figures provided further evidence
of a diminishing amount of spare capacity in the economy, although the
consequent fears of inflation and further base rate rises were only two of
several factors depressing equity and bond prices.
In London, the FT-SE 100 index closed 31.8 points down at 3,065.8, while
gilt-edged government bonds lost about  1/2 point.
The Central Statistical Office reported that output of the production
industries, including manufacturing, oil and mineral extraction and
electricity, gas and water supply, jumped a seasonally adjusted 1.1 per cent
between August and September.
It also revised upwards statistics for July and August, estimating the
present annual 'trend' rate of growth for production industry output at 6
per cent.
Manufacturing output, which accounts for just over 84 per cent of industrial
production, rose by a seasonally adjusted 0.6 per cent in September compared
with August. The CSO said manufacturing output was now growing at a trend
rate of 5.5 per cent.
The Treasury welcomed yesterday's production figures, although it declined
to comment on the policy implications. Officials said growth was broadly
based and noted that the growth of output of investment goods, at 1.8 per
cent between the second and third quarters, was stronger than that of the
consumer or intermediate-goods sectors.
September's surge in industrial activity brought output of the production
industries to a new high. But it restored manufacturing output only to the
level of July 1990, on the eve of the last recession.
Production industry output has been buoyed by exceptionally strong oil and
gas production since the beginning of last year. Oil and gas output now
stands at a high after increasing by 3.5 per cent between August and
September as several fields returned to normal production after maintenance
closures in August.
As overall industrial production accounts for some 28 per cent of gross
domestic product, yesterday's figures are expected to boost third-quarter
GDP growth by at least 0.1 percentage points. If there are no substantial
downward revisions in other areas of economic activity, some economists
believe the UK may have grown at about 3.8 per cent in the year to the third
quarter compared with the provisional 3.6 per cent growth reported last
month.
The Confederation of British Industry, which will today hear a speech from
Mr Clarke at its annual conference in Birmingham, warned yesterday there was
no need for UK rates to rise.
Robust growth seen for industrial output, Page 9
Bonds, Page 28
Currencies, Page 36
London stocks, Page 46
</TEXT>
