<HEADLINE>
FT  07 NOV 94 / Companies to test electronic filing of tax returns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY, Accountancy Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A sample group of up to 1,000 UK companies will from today have their
corporation tax returns filed directly to the Inland Revenue by computer
link.
The scheme aims to replace costly letters and telephone calls and to bring
closer the goal of direct filing from accountants, companies and home-based
personal computers.
If the pilot exercise succeeds, a national system of electronic filing may
be available for all the 1m corporation tax returns made in a year.
In 1996 the Revenue plans to try the system on its new self-assessment
personal tax forms. Up to 5m taxpayers may be using the so-called Electronic
Lodgement Service through accountants by 2001.
The Big Six accountancy firms, acting as agents for clients, have joined the
project.
The Revenue, which is under government pressure to cut costs, sees large
savings in the scheme, with the aim of eventually eliminating routine paper
tax correspondence.
Accountants and other agents envisage fewer immediate benefits, and are
pressing the Revenue to introduce a flat-rate payment to those filing
electronically.
They are also unhappy with the costs of the pilot project, which initially
has to be run in tandem with the existing paper-based system.
The voluntary project, running until March 1995, aims to test the technology
and see whether accountants, software houses and the Revenue can work
together.
From today, tax returns from the sample companies will be filed via modem
from the accountants through a message 'gateway' at the Revenue's offices in
Basingstoke.
The electronic version of the tax return will be the one used by the Revenue
 -not the paper backup. The software is being provided by Taxsoft and Data
Sciences.
Details, Page 8
</TEXT>
