<HEADLINE>
FT  07 NOV 94 / This Week: The mystery that is Formula One - Sport
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEITH WHEATLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Hamlet should have been running Formula One motor racing. 'The play's the
thing,' he urged as the Danish monarchy struggled to shake off some terrible
PR. Despite a season that could scarcely have begun with worse portents,
including the death of Ayrton Senna and the Benetton fire, somehow the Grand
Prix circus is once again delivering the goods.
The duel between Michael Schumacher and Damon Hill for the championship is
providing a finish that hasn't been as tight or absorbing since Senna v
Prost in 1991, while the newly-announced partnership of Mercedes and McLaren
shows that F1 is still the motor-sport arena that counts with the biggest
motor companies.
Worldwide television audiences have shown a huge increase, against all
pre-season predictions. ('Don't under-estimate the morbid desire to watch
the 20th slo-mo replay of Senna's death,' a cynic in the pit-lane cautioned
me). In his office above Knightsbridge, in London, barrister Max Mosley, who
is the ringmaster of Grand Prix, is cautiously satisfied.
Overall, he says, the most important end-of-term conclusion is that the
officials are back in charge of their massively powerful vehicle.
'Basically, we try to slow the cars down and the teams attempt to speed them
up,' he says. 'This season we have proved that we can control the
technology, for the good of the sport.'
Regulating a game like soccer - 22 lads and a ball - cannot be anything like
as difficult as regulating Grand Prix. The sport lives or dies by its
creation of technical regulations to produce closely-matched racing. Yet
when every Formula One car receives between 50 and 100 modifications between
each race, the task of scrutineering becomes impossible.
'The days when you employed an engineer with a micrometer, tape measure and
oily rag are over,' says Mosley. 'A device like traction control, for
example, will have several million lines of code in the on-board computer.
Checking something like that requires an expert.'
Last winter the governing bodies agonised over repeated criticisms that the
average F1 race had become a dollar-driven technology procession. The
best-funded teams had cars that were unbeatable. Drivers were becoming jaded
button-pushers, ran the argument. Mosley, a former competitor, was
sympathetic.
Traction control was banned, and next season sees smaller three-litre
engines and revised aerofoil systems, all designed to reward driver skill
and innovative low-budget teams.
Yet surely all this is window-dressing. In terms of results, nothing has
changed. After Williams, McLaren, Benetton and Ferrari, the average
non-afficianado would struggle to name an F1 team. The only glimpse most of
us have of a Simtek or a Ligier is when the on-board camera on Schumacher's
car shows them being lapped.
'I think we've closed the gap somewhat,' claims Mosley, stopwatch and
calculator in hand. 'The top 20 cars this season would have lap times within
three seconds of each other. I don't think Formula One has ever been so
competitive.'
There are those who say that the sport created its own suspense and stopped
the season being a total Benetton benefit when it banned Schumacher for two
races and disqualified him after he had crossed the line first in Belgium.
It put Damon Hill back in with a chance, which he consolidated by winning
the Japanese Grand Prix yesterday. Does the sport now require quasi-judicial
intervention to ensure that excitent is maintained?
'People talk blithely about a Golden Age,' counters Mosley. 'But there were
huge disparities in performance in those days. One Mercedes would lap the
field, and if there were three Mercedes, they'd all lap you. A podium result
remains very, very hard to get.'
Without huge financial muscle, all the talent and engineering imagination in
the world is just froth in Grand Prix racing. Jordan is now being spoken of
as a potential force for 1995. Why? Because it has been adopted by Peugeot,
discarded as engine-suppliers by a McLaren happily besotted with mighty
Mercedes.
'The really big money is now being spent by the major manufacturers who
provide the engines,' says Mosley. Although critics of F1 profligacy
invariably take cigarette sponsors as their example, it is now the motor
industry that is calling the shots. When Nigel Mansell came back for one
race in mid-season it was at the insistence of Renault, at the budgetary
heart of the Williams team.
Worried by the adulatory coverage Peugeot was receiving, Renault needed a PR
coup on the eve of the French Grand Prix. Again, it was Renault which booked
Mansell to drive for the last three events of this season. Only a company
that big could afford to pay him the Dollars 1.5m he was demanding per
appearance. There was also a 'disappointment' clause. If Williams/Renault
told Mansell he was 'excused driving' at Jerez, Suzuka or Adelaide, then the
driver was to receive an additional Dollars 3m for hurt pride.
Grand Prix racing remains an enigma. Much of it is unappealing or just plain
boring. When danger delivers the goods, with a fatality, it is revolting.
Yet it goes from strength to strength, recovering miraculously from
near-mortal wounds. Mosley talks about an innate mysticism. He says: 'No one
knows why Formula One is so popular. But it is. So don't let's change it too
much.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7948 Racing, Including Track Operation.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 13
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT944-11356</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EKGC8AB9FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941107
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 NOV 94 / This Week: Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALKARIM JIVANI, TV Editor of Time Out
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Martin Chuzzlewit (Monday, 9.00-10.30pm, BBC2) is ready to roll over us in a
wave of carriages and corsets. Paul Schofield plays Chuzzlewit Pere with
aplomb; as if this wasn't enough, he also takes on the part of Anthony
Chuzzlewit. In the opening episode, Chuzzlewit Fils, as played by Ben Walden
(son of Brian), is somewhat leaden but this is compensated for by a splendid
supporting cast, and there is John Mills still to come. Two endings have
been shot. The one preferred by David Lodge, who adapted the novel, is an
upbeat one with three weddings; that favoured by director Pedr James is a
downbeat monologue delivered by Tom Pinch. Despite this mild controversy,
the drama delivers exactly what you expect, making it a bit of an old
chestnut, pleasing though it is when served roasted over a crackling fire by
extras in wigs and false moustaches.
Dominick Dunne became the leading American crime reporter with his coverage
of the Claus Von Bulow case and the Menendez brothers' trial. 'Dominick did
a better job than the prosecutor in the Menendez case', says the editor of
Vanity Fair, as well he might since Dunne is one of his star writers.
Omnibus (Tuesday, 10.20-11.10pm, BBC1) profiles the novelist and writer who
was born into a wealthy East Coast family, hit hard times and then rebuilt
his career and life. The result is a fascinating piece, not least because of
the comments made by the Menendez defence lawyer with whom Dunne has carried
on a public feud.
Richard Curtis, who wrote Four Weddings And A Funeral, has come up with
another altar-obsessed comedy, The Vicar Of Dibbley (Thursday, 8.30-9.00pm,
BBC1). Dawn French is the new vicar of the eponymous village which is
expecting atestosterone-driven prelate and has to adjust. This has the same
essentially English approach to comedy as Curtis's hit film, but on a
smaller scale - more like Two Christenings And A Small Sherry.
Terence Rattigan is enjoying a success he hasn't had since John Osborne
looked back in anger. After a London revival last year, The Deep Blue Sea is
getting a BBC production (Saturday, 9.30-11.10pm, BBC2), directed by Karel
Reisz. This is a gritty play, far removed from the polite pieces Rattigan is
associated with. It begins with an attempted suicide. Penelope Wilton has
perfected her Hester Collyer and gets splendid support from Ian Holm and
Colin Firth as the two men in her life.
Ever since Hilda Ogden hung up her pinny, the mantle of loveable TV shrew
has settled round Thora Hird's shoulders, and this week Melvynn Bragg pays
tribute in The South Bank Show (Sunday, 10.45-11.45pm, ITV). Dame Thora is
now 83 and well into her anecdotage. But it hardly matters since the
anecdotes are of vintage quality ,supplemented by clips from her 60-year
career.
</TEXT>
