<HEADLINE>
FT  07 NOV 94 / Midlands groups see improvement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Capital spending by quoted west Midlands companies remained flat in the year
to June, although money spent on acquisitions rose 33 per cent.
The findings emerge from the annual analysis of 133 quoted companies in the
region by accountants KPMG Peat Marwick. It shows the companies moving out
of recession with collective pre-tax profits in 1993-94 of Pounds 2.01bn
compared with Pounds 1.37bn in 1992-93.
Capital spending over the period was Pounds 1.55bn, a slight increase on the
Pounds 1.53bn recorded in 1992-93, but this rise came after three years of
cuts. KPMG noted, however, that in the engineering sector, the staple of the
region's industry, capital spending was lower than in 1992-93.
Higher profitability encouraged directors to pay themselves more. After
three years of little or no pay increases, the average director's pay rose
in 1993-94 to Pounds 82,800 from Pounds 73,950 the year before.
The average rise for employees was 5 per cent, but this included the cost of
increased overtime.
In the construction, motors and industrial materials sectors companies are
still cutting their workforces.
West Midlands Plc, annual report 1994. KPMG Peat Marwick, 2 Cornwall Street,
Birmingham B3 2DL. Free.
</TEXT>
