<HEADLINE>
FT  07 NOV 94 / Electronic tax return spells end for dreaded form: The
launch of a computer link between accountants and the Inland Revenue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For almost as long as tax has been paid it has been accompanied by the
dreaded tax form. That link may be broken from today with the introduction
by the Inland Revenue of its Electronic Lodgement System (ELS).
The system will link the computer systems of taxpayers' agents, normally
accountants, with those of the Revenue.
The savings in the long-term should be huge. Mr Ian Barlow, tax partner at
accountants KPMG Peat Marwick, estimates that it costs Pounds 15 merely to
store an average tax file in a filing cabinet for a year. The likely savings
potential at the Revenue, which dealt last year with 30m returns from
individuals and companies, could also be huge.
Few doubt the long-term logic of electronic tax returns and most admire the
speed with which the Revenue has got to grips with the technology. But the
first phase of the system illustrates some potential problems.
Paper is proving resilient to change. Until later this month, when changes
are expected to be announced in the Budget, a duplicate paper tax process
must run in tandem with the new system. Later that may go - but the need for
a signed authorisation from the taxpayer may persist.
Joining the system is also proving expensive. While the Revenue is paying
for most of the transmission costs, the Big Six accountancy firms are aware
that while the capital costs of starting up may be small the investment in
time is considerable.
For smaller firms the expense rises proportionately. One smaller firm, HW
Fisher, has been included in the pilot scheme to help judge the issues. The
Revenue estimates the first year cost as Pounds 750, but this presumes that
the smaller firm has a relatively expensive personal computer facility
already in place. Given that the system is voluntary, there seems to be
little reason for smaller agents take part.
Accountants are not the only agents with doubts. The personal tax
sub-committee of the British Bankers' Association believes its members will
join an ELS to carry its existing tax return business. But it sees no future
for a high-volume business based on high-street banks.
Mr John Whiting, tax partner with Price Waterhouse and chairman of the
business forum for ELS, is well aware that the business argument has yet to
be won. He believes greater incentives need to be found to get accountants
and the public to file electronically.
In New Zealand, where electronic lodgement operates, 80 per cent of
taxpayers get refunds within 14 days when using the electronic system. Paper
returns earn refunds in two to three months. The UK system will not contain
the same rewards.
'We do need to incentivise our system,' said Mr Whiting. The forum is
putting together a 'shopping list' of possible options to make it worthwhile
for accountants to enter a fully fledged system.
But the Big Six are taking part in the pilot scheme, providing some proof
that the long-term benefits of moving to the system outweigh the short-term
costs. Negotiation may be needed in the next year but the outcome seems
certain.
Accountants do not see the system as a threat to their jobs - quite the
reverse. Proficiency in filing in a tax form on-screen, once a year, will
not come easily and accountants, working with volume, are well placed to
pick up the business.
The revenue envisages that some taxpayers may one day file their returns
from home but others will transfer the information to a disk and take it to
an agent - or even to a central 'tax shop' or service point in a Post
Office.
But for the Revenue, and therefore the taxpayer, the great prize is likely
to be increased accuracy in tax returns and a big cut in the time spent
correcting errors on hand-written forms.
</TEXT>
