<HEADLINE>
FT  07 NOV 94 / Agencies set up travel brand
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More than 600 independent travel agents are today adopting a common brand,
making them the UK's biggest grouping of travel retailers after Lunn Poly.
The retailers, all members of the National Association of Independent Travel
Agents, will display the brand Advantage Travel Centres alongside their
existing names.
The move follows concern among smaller companies about the growth of big
travel retailers and their links with leading tour operators.
The two biggest travel retailers, Lunn Poly and Going Places, are owned by
the two leading tour operators, Thomson and Airtours respectively. Lunn Poly
has 742 shops and Going Places has 562.
The Office of Fair Trading said in August that the links between big tour
operators and travel agents did not restrict consumer choice or prevent
smaller companies from selling holidays.
But small travel agency companies have continued to argue that it is
difficult for them to match the advertising budgets of big companies. They
have also said big tour operators have supported their affiliated travel
agents during discount campaigns, when retailers forfeit their commission.
Independents have found it difficult to match these discounts.
