<HEADLINE>
FT  07 NOV 94 / Business rate rise forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rating experts are expecting Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, to announce
an increase in the uniform business rate in his Budget on November 29.
The new rate, with an assessment of the rateable value for individual
properties, based on commercial rents, will determine how much businesses
will pay in the five years from April 1 1995.
While rents have risen in most areas since the last revaluation five years
ago, large falls in London and a conservative approach by local valuation
offices - to reduce the number of successful appeals - are likely to result
in a lower average rateable value.
If this proves to be correct the chancellor will have to increase the rate
from this year's level of 42.3p in the pound to maintain the amount raised.
The government has said that it does not intend to increase the overall
burden of taxation but regional changes in rents in the past five years mean
that the distribution will change dramatically.
The chart (above) is based on rental value data for 50 towns in England and
Wales and assumes that the chancellor sets a rate of 43.5p in the pound.
Mr Brian Hardy, rating partner at Jones Lang Wootton, the surveyors, said
that rates on the best City offices could fall from Pounds 25 a sq ft to
Pounds 10 or less.
Office occupiers in Birmingham are likely to see rates double to Pounds 16 a
sq ft.
The swings for retail and industrial occupiers are likely to be less severe
because rents have risen less.
The government has said that increases will be phased, so that rates bills
will not rise by more than 20 per cent a year in real terms.
It is not clear how quickly businesses with lower rateable values, mostly in
London, will be allowed to feel the benefit.
Even if reductions are phased over two or three years, falling rates are
likely to boost the City office market by reducing the overall cost of
occupying space.
Regional centres are not expected to suffer, because rates are a much
smaller proportion of overall occupancy costs.
</TEXT>
