<HEADLINE>
FT  07 NOV 94 / TUC demands Pounds 1bn boost for employment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Employment Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government should spend Pounds 1.15bn on measures to cut unemployment,
raising the money required from the abolition of tax relief on
profit-related pay schemes and a crackdown on tax evasion, the Trades Union
Congress says in its Budget submission published today.
The submission represents a significant shift in union thought, with its
emphasis on the theme of 'making benefits work for the unemployed'. It has
tried to break from previous practice by not drawing up a list of demands
that Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, would dismiss. The TUC is trying to
exercise an influence by suggesting measures which would go with, rather
than against, the grain of government policy.
Mr John Monks, TUC general secretary, said that unions shared the views of
the chancellor and the Confederation of British Industry, that 'the welfare
state should be helping the unemployed into jobs and training'.
The TUC proposals include calls for:
A reduction in the poverty and unemployment trap caused by the loss of
benefit as earnings rise.
A cut in the tax rates on workers earning more than Pounds 57 a week by the
abolition of the 2 per cent National Insurance entry fee.
A reduction in employers' National Insurance contributions as an incentive
to create more low-paid jobs.
The introduction of a training levy on all employers with lower National
Insurance contributions for those achieving Investors in People status.
The provision of subsidies for employers to take on long-term jobless.
The submission quotes pointedly from Mr Clarke's Mais lecture earlier this
year, in which he said a strong welfare state could 'complement, not hinder,
flexible markets by reducing fear of change and opposition to it'.
Mr Monks said: 'We have presented him with a mutually reinforcing package of
proposals that the present government could implement.'
Other proposals include: a Pounds 300m increase in funding of income support
and family credit; Pounds 750m more for child benefit which would remain
available for all families; Pounds 100m for higher benefits for those on
training programmes, as well as stabilising public investment at its present
levels as a share of national income. The last would provide an extra Pounds
12bn over three years, creating 300,000 jobs, the TUC said.
Meanwhile, in an interview on GMTV, Mr Monks eased union pressure on Labour
to commit itself to a minimum wage of more than Pounds 4 an hour. Mr Monks
backed the long-standing formula of Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor,
that the level of the the minimum wage should be set 'in the light of the
economic circumstances at the time'.
</TEXT>
