<HEADLINE>
FT  07 NOV 94 / Help for long-term unemployed urged
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Adam Smith Institute, the independent free-market research group, calls
today for measures to create work for the long-term unemployed.
It suggests that they should be exempt from paying tax and National
Insurance for two years after they secure work. The institute also calls for
the creation of 'green-light zones or estates' for two years in inner
cities, where companies with an annual turnover of Pounds 500,000 or less
could establish themselves without being subject to planning permission or
other regulations. It says this would create jobs in areas such as retail
distribution and mini-cab services.
It adds: 'These measures will provide a rung to help the long-term
unemployed and economically deprived areas to climb up into the normal
wage-earning and productive economy.'
Operation Underclass. Adam Smith Institute, 23 Great Smith Street, London
SW1P 3BL. Pounds 10.00
