<HEADLINE>
FT  07 NOV 94 / Scharping appeals for amnesty on Stasi links
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Rudolf Scharping, the leader of Germany's opposition Social Democrats,
has called for a partial amnesty for those who co-operated with former east
Germany's Stasi secret police.
The plea re-opens an issue that has divided east and west Germans and has
pitted east Germans against one another as they come to terms with one of
the most hated and insidious institutions of the communist period.
Mr Scharping said it was time to grant some partial amnesty for former Stasi
employees on the grounds that it was preventing 'inner unification' and it
was time to rehabilitate some of these people. An amnesty might also have
the affect of diluting some support for the PDS, the successor to the former
east German Communist party, which contains former Stasi members.
More than 109,000 people are estimated to have collaborated with the Stasi.
A law was passed in December 1991 enabling east Germans access to their
files. It also allows public and private institutions access to screen
employees.
Mr Scharping's plea was supported by Mr Stefan Heym, the east German writer
and member of the PDS who was recently elected to the Bundestag, or lower
house.
But Chancellor Helmut Kohl's governing Christian Democratic party and senior
members of the Gauck Commission, the institution responsible for supervising
the files, have opposed any amnesty.
'The time has not yet come, either for an amnesty or to close the files,'
said Mr Hansjorg Geiger, deputy to Mr Joachim Gauck, the former east German
Lutheran pastor who heads the Commission.
Mr Geiger said there were still more than 400,000 outstanding requests by
individuals wishing to see their files and the commission was receiving
about 500 requests a day. By last April more than 720,000, most of them east
Germans, had applied to see whether their names had appeared on any of the
files.
The files are located in the giant former Stasi headquarters in east Berlin.
Although the Stasi tried to burn or shred as many files as possible in late
1989, the Gauck commission still has over 180km of files containing 6m names
 -about 4m east Germans and 2m west Germans.
The material remains politically explosive. Prominent east German
politicians, including Mr Gregor Gysi, the parliamentary head of the PDS, is
alleged to have collaborated with the Stasi but he has vehemently denied any
of these allegations.
Opinion among east Germans remains divided about keeping the files open. Mr
Jens Reich, a physicist and member of the former east German opposition,
believes the files should be kept open to show the psychological and
political nature of totalitarianism as well as the nature of collaboration
or resistance under such a system.
But other prominent east Germans, including Mr Friedrich Schorlemmer, a
Lutheran theologian who opposed the former communist government, wants the
files closed because they impose a permanent burden of guilt on east
Germans.
</TEXT>
<XX>
