<HEADLINE>
FT  07 NOV 94 / Strong UK industrial growth forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, RODERICK ORAM and ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK manufacturing industry, battered by contraction and plant closures during
the 1980s, may be entering its strongest period of growth for 30 years.
Forecasts by the London Business School predict that manufacturing output
will rise by 4.5 per cent this year and 5.6 per cent in 1995.
Manufacturing production from 1994 to 1998 will, according to the school,
show an average annual increase of 4.3 per cent. If achieved, that would
make it the best five-year period of industrial growth since 1964-68.
However, a more gloomy report published yesterday by the National
Manufacturing Council - an arm of the Confederation of British Industry -
suggests that some of British manufacturing's traditional difficulties,
including poor productivity and low investment, may become a barrier to
achieving the predicted output growth.
Manufacturing productivity, the council said, still lags some 20 per cent to
40 per cent behind output per head in leading foreign economies, and it
warned that the gap might grow as economies abroad recovered.
'We need more investment in our plants and people,' the council said in its
annual report. It added: 'The rate (of industrial growth) is insufficient to
allow Britain to catch up with its main competitors, such as Germany, Japan
and the US.'
The council added other concerns about a manufacturing recovery, including a
historically sluggish rate of investment, slower turnover of stocks than
principal competitor countries, a persistent trade deficit in manufactured
goods and lower workforce skills than competitor economies.
London Business School, taking a more optimistic view, says changes on the
supply side of the economy meant that handicaps once dubbed the 'British
disease' - low productivity growth, poor industrial relations and a
declining share of world trade - were 'a thing of the past'. Improvements in
those areas, combined with shifts towards investment and export-led growth
and a lower exchange rate, were reasons for expecting that manufacturing
industry would perform well.
The view that the overall recovery in the UK economy remains strong is
supported by Mr Alan Davies, chief economist of Barclays Bank, in the bank's
quarterly economic review today.
TUC demands Pounds 1bn boost for employment, Page 7
Consumer credit growth slows, Page 8
</TEXT>
