<HEADLINE>
FT  05 NOV 94 / International Company News: PowerPC alliance to be
strengthened
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
International Business Machines, Apple Computer and Motorola will on Monday
announce plans to develop a common specification for personal computers
based on the PowerPC microprocessor chips that the three companies have
jointly developed.
The agreement builds on the PowerPC alliance formed by the companies three
years ago which was established to challenge the PC industry standards for
hardware and software based on Intel microprocessors and Microsoft software.
The success of the alliance has been limited by incompatibilities between
Apple's Power Macintosh computers and the PowerPC computers built by
Motorola and IBM. On Monday, the companies will announce that they have
agreed to eliminate these incompatibilities. But it will be two years before
computers based on the new standard are available.
Talks among the three companies have been underway for several months,
fuelling rumours that either IBM or Motorola might acquire, or take an
equity stake in Apple. IBM had also been reported to be close to reaching an
agreement to license Apple's Macintosh software.
But in the event, the new agreement between Apple , IBM and Motorola applies
only to the hardware specification for PCs.
An important goal of the new pact is to encourage third party software
companies to develop applications for PowerPC computers. The lack of
software for PowerPC was cited by IBM when it postponed introduction of its
planned Power Personal range of PCs last month.
The new design will run a variety of operating systems including Apple's Mac
OS, IBM's OS/2 and others. If developers could write software that runs on
several operating systems on one machine, with only slight modifications,
they might be more inclined to write software for the PowerPC computers ,
analysts said.
</TEXT>
